{
  "$schema": "https://aka.ms/codetour-schema",
  "title": "Architecture Overview",
  "description": "A guided walk through llm-valet's two parallel abstractions — resources (machine monitoring) and providers (LLM serving) — and how they meet in the watchdog and API.",
  "steps": [
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 57,
      "title": "1 · Two parallel abstractions",
      "description": "The whole system is built on two symmetric [Abstract Base Classes](https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html): `ResourceCollector` and `LLMProvider`.\n\n`ResourceCollector` (here) monitors the machine — RAM, CPU, GPU, disk.\n\n`LLMProvider` (in `providers/base.py`) is the abstraction layer for local LLM serving software. Any provider that can be paused, resumed, started, and stopped can be implemented as a concrete subclass — Ollama ships in v1.0, with LM Studio, vLLM, exo, KoboldCPP, and others as natural future targets. The rest of the system (watchdog, API) only ever calls the `LLMProvider` interface, so swapping or adding a provider requires no changes outside its own file.\n\nNeither ABC depends on the other. The watchdog wires them together."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 10,
      "title": "2 · Metric dataclasses",
      "description": "`PressureLevel` + the four metric dataclasses (`MemoryMetrics`, `CPUMetrics`, `GPUMetrics`, `DiskMetrics`) are the currency of the system — every decision downstream is made from a single `SystemMetrics` snapshot.\n\n**Occupancy vs. demand — why both exist**\n\n`used_pct` measures *occupancy*: how much of the RAM pool is in use. `PressureLevel` measures *demand*: whether processes are actively competing for memory the OS can't readily supply. These are not the same thing, and on macOS they frequently diverge. The OS deliberately fills RAM with file caches and pre-warmed apps — 90% occupancy can coexist with `NORMAL` pressure because nothing is actually contesting that memory. Pressure only rises when the OS has to make a painful tradeoff: compress pages, evict a cache, or delay an allocation. On Apple Silicon the distinction matters even more, because CPU and GPU draw from the same unified pool — pressure reflects demand across both.\n\n**Cross-platform grounding**\n\n- **macOS**: native kernel API (`memory_pressure` CLI), reports `normal / warn / critical` directly.\n- **Linux**: PSI (Pressure Stall Information, `/proc/pressure/memory`) measures how long tasks stall waiting for memory — the closest Linux equivalent, though availability varies by kernel version.\n- **Windows**: no native demand signal. `PressureLevel` is derived from `used_pct` thresholds in `_pressure_from_pct()` (`resources/windows.py`): `< 75%` → `NORMAL`, `≥ 75%` → `WARN`, `≥ 90%` → `CRITICAL`. These are currently hardcoded and independent of the user's `ram_pause_pct` config — a future Windows implementation pass should make them user-adjustable to match the config-driven approach on other platforms.\n\n**Optional fields**\n\nSome metrics simply don't exist on every machine. `GPUMetrics` fields like `vram_used_mb` and `compute_pct` are typed `int | None` or `float | None` — Python's notation for \"this value may be absent.\" On a machine with no accessible GPU driver, those fields are `None` rather than a misleading zero. Callers check `supported_metrics()` first to know which fields are safe to use."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 99,
      "title": "3 · ThresholdEngine: pure logic, no I/O",
      "description": "`ThresholdEngine` is stateless — it takes `SystemMetrics` + `ResourceThresholds` and returns `(should_pause: bool, reason: str)`. No network calls, no filesystem reads, no psutil.\n\nThis makes it trivially unit-testable: pass in a crafted `SystemMetrics`, assert the decision. The watchdog owns all state (counters, timers); `ThresholdEngine` just evaluates the instantaneous snapshot."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/resources/base.py",
      "line": 124,
      "title": "4 · Apple Silicon: why memory_pressure is NOT a trigger",
      "description": "On Apple Silicon, loading a large model into unified memory routinely causes transient `CRITICAL` pressure readings — even when RAM% is within the user's configured threshold. If we used `memory_pressure CRITICAL` as an independent pause trigger, every model load would immediately pause the service.\n\nSo `PressureLevel` is reported in `/metrics` for informational purposes only. `ram_pause_pct` (from config) is the authoritative trigger. This is the most counter-intuitive design decision in the codebase."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/providers/base.py",
      "line": 24,
      "title": "5 · LLMProvider: the other half",
      "description": "`LLMProvider` is the contract every provider implementation must satisfy.\n\nThe critical distinction between `pause`/`resume` and `start`/`stop`: **pause** unloads the model from memory but leaves the service running (fast — seconds). **stop** shuts the service down entirely (slow — 30–90s to come back). The watchdog only ever calls `pause`/`resume`; `start`/`stop` are reserved for the API's manual control surface.\n\nOllama v1.0 is the only concrete implementation. `LM Studio`, `vLLM`, and `MLX` are post-v1.0 parked features."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/watchdog.py",
      "line": 14,
      "title": "6 · FSM: five states",
      "description": "The watchdog is a five-state machine:\n\n```\nRUNNING → PAUSING → PAUSED → RESUMING → RUNNING\n                ↕\n          PROVIDER_DOWN\n```\n\n`PAUSING` and `RESUMING` are intra-tick transient states — they exist only while the provider call is in-flight. `PROVIDER_DOWN` handles unexpected Ollama crashes so the FSM doesn't stay stuck at `RUNNING` when the service exits."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/watchdog.py",
      "line": 34,
      "title": "7 · Watchdog constructor: composed, not coupled",
      "description": "The watchdog receives a `LLMProvider` and a `ResourceCollector` by injection. It never calls `psutil` directly for resource data, and it never imports a concrete provider.\n\nThis keeps the watchdog testable: swap in mock implementations and assert state transitions without touching the OS or a real Ollama instance. `ThresholdEngine` is constructed internally because it's pure logic with no external surface."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/watchdog.py",
      "line": 78,
      "title": "8 · Manual pause sync — why this exists",
      "description": "`notify_manual_pause()` and `notify_manual_resume()` are called by the API after a successful `/pause` or `/resume` request.\n\nWithout these, the FSM and the provider are out of sync: the user manually pauses, but the watchdog still thinks the state is `RUNNING` and will try to pause again on the next tick — or worse, immediately resume because resources look fine.\n\nThe API writes the outcome; the watchdog syncs its view to match. This is the handshake that keeps both state machines coherent."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/watchdog.py",
      "line": 101,
      "title": "9 · The tick: where everything meets",
      "description": "Every `check_interval_seconds`, `_tick()` runs this sequence:\n\n1. Health-probe the provider — detect unexpected crashes → `PROVIDER_DOWN`\n2. `collector.collect()` → `SystemMetrics`\n3. `_detect_game()` → scan psutil for `steamapps/common` processes\n4. `ThresholdEngine.evaluate(metrics)` → `(resource_pressure, reason)`\n5. Accumulate CPU ticks for the sustained-seconds window\n6. Resolve `should_pause` — game OR (resource pressure AND not CPU-only-or-sustained)\n7. If `RUNNING` and `should_pause` → `_transition_to_paused()`\n8. If `PAUSED` and not `should_pause` → check grace period → `_transition_to_running()`"
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/api.py",
      "line": 191,
      "title": "10 · Security middleware: order matters",
      "description": "Three middleware layers are stacked in this order:\n\n1. **TrustedHostMiddleware** (T2 — DNS rebinding) — rejects any `Host` header not in the allowlist. Must be outermost so a rebinding attack is stopped before the request reaches any handler.\n2. **Body size limit** (64 KB) — drops oversized requests before JSON parsing. `Content-Length` alone is insufficient because chunked transfer omits it; the middleware drains and buffers the stream.\n3. **CORSMiddleware** (T3) — `allow_origins` is empty by default; never `\"*\"`. Cross-origin JS cannot reach the API unless an explicit origin is added in config.\n\nMiddleware in FastAPI/Starlette executes in reverse registration order (last-added runs first on request). `TrustedHostMiddleware` must be added first so it executes last on the way in — closest to the network."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/api.py",
      "line": 263,
      "title": "11 · Auth: localhost exempt, LAN requires key",
      "description": "`require_api_key` is injected as a FastAPI dependency on every mutating endpoint.\n\nRequests from `127.0.0.1` or `::1` bypass the key check entirely — if you're local, you're trusted. Any other source (LAN, VPN) must supply a valid `X-API-Key`. If `api_key` is not set in config and the host is bound to `0.0.0.0`, all LAN requests get 403 rather than silently passing.\n\nThis mirrors the default bind: `127.0.0.1` is safe without auth; `0.0.0.0` is opt-in and requires a key."
    },
    {
      "file": "llm_valet/static/index.html",
      "line": 1774,
      "title": "12 · WebUI: textContent, never innerHTML",
      "description": "All dynamic data from the API is written via `element.textContent`, never `element.innerHTML`. This is the T5 (XSS) mitigation.\n\n`innerHTML` interprets the string as HTML — if any API field ever contains `<script>` or an event handler, it executes. `textContent` treats the string as literal text and escapes it automatically.\n\nThe one exception is the resource bar segments, which are built with `document.createElement()` + `appendChild()` — DOM construction rather than HTML string concatenation. Same guarantee, different mechanism."
    }
  ]
}
